1. Assignment Overview¶

In this assignment, you will delve into the world of Autoencoders. Autoencoders are a type of neural network that are trained to attempt to copy their input to their output. They work by narrowing down the input into a lower-dimensional code and then reconstructing the output from this representation. This lab will guide you through the concepts of autoencoding, from simple architectures to more complex, variational autoencoders (VAEs).

You will get hands-on experience by implementing these models using PyTorch, training them on datasets, and analyzing their performance. By the end of this lab, you should be able to:

  • Understand the theory and intuition behind Autoencoders and Variational Autoencoders.
  • Implement and train Autoencoders and VAEs using PyTorch.
  • Use Autoencoders for tasks such as image reconstruction, noise reduction, and data generation.
  • Evaluate the performance of your Autoencoder models.

In the decoder, implement three  deconvolutional layers followed by ReLU activations (again, excluding the last layer), and remember to apply a sigmoid activation layer at last as well (Why?) Specifically, using the PyTorch library, create the decoder with the following specific parameters:
    

      

    • First deconvolutional layer: {Number of input channels: 64 | Number of output channels: 32 | Kernel size: 7}

    • Third deconvolutional layer: {Number of input channels: 16 | Number of output channels: 1 | Kernel size: 3 | Stride: 2 | Padding: 1, Output Padding: 1}

In [4]:



     


class Autoencoder(nn.Module):
    def __init__(self):
        super(Autoencoder, self).__init__()
        # =================== YOUR CODE STARTS HERE ==================
        self.encoder = nn.Sequential(
             nn.Conv2d(1, 16, kernel_size=3, stride=2, padding=1),
             nn.ReLU(),
             nn.Conv2d(16, 32, kernel_size=3, stride=2, padding=1),
             nn.ReLU(),
             nn.Conv2d(32, 64, kernel_size=7)
         )
        # # ==================== YOUR CODE ENDS HERE ===================

        # =================== YOUR CODE STARTS HERE ==================

        self.decoder = nn.Sequential(
            nn.ConvTranspose2d(64, 32, kernel_size=7),
            nn.ReLU(),
            nn.ConvTranspose2d(32, 16, kernel_size=3, stride=2, padding=1, output_padding=1),
            nn.ReLU(),
            nn.ConvTranspose2d(16, 1, kernel_size=3, stride=2, padding=1, output_padding=1),
            nn.Sigmoid()
        )


        # ==================== YOUR CODE ENDS HERE ===================

    def forward(self, x):
        x = self.encoder(x)
        x = self.decoder(x)
        return x

def train(model, num_epochs=5, batch_size=64, learning_rate=1e-3):
    torch.manual_seed(42)
    criterion = nn.MSELoss() # mean square error loss
    optimizer = torch.optim.Adam(model.parameters(),
                                 lr=learning_rate,
                                 weight_decay=1e-5)
    train_loader = torch.utils.data.DataLoader(mnist_data,
                                               batch_size=batch_size,
                                               shuffle=True)
    outputs = []
    # =================== YOUR CODE STARTS HERE ==================
    # Hint: You need to define (two) nested `for` loops.
    for epoch in range(num_epochs):
        for data in train_loader:
          img,_ = data
          recon = model(img)

          loss = criterion(recon,img)
          optimizer.zero_grad()
          loss.backward()

          optimizer.step()


          outputs.append((epoch, img, recon))
        print(f"Epoch [{epoch+1}/{num_epochs}], Loss: {loss.item():.4f}")



    # ==================== YOUR CODE ENDS HERE ===================
    return outputs

def train(model, num_epochs=5, batch_size=64, learning_rate=1e-3):
    torch.manual_seed(42)
    criterion = nn.MSELoss() # mean square error loss
    optimizer = torch.optim.Adam(model.parameters(),
                                 lr=learning_rate,
                                 weight_decay=1e-5)
    train_loader = torch.utils.data.DataLoader(mnist_data,
                                               batch_size=batch_size,
                                               shuffle=True)
    noise = 0.5
    outputs = []
    # =================== YOUR CODE STARTS HERE ==================
    # Hint: Again, you need to define two nested `for` loops.
    # Hint: You can create the nosiy image like this: img_noisy = img + noise * torch.randn(*img.shape)
    #       followed by img_noisy = np.clip(img_noisy, 0, 1). The reconstructed image would be this noisy
    #       image passed through our model (defined autoencoder.)

    for epoch in range(num_epochs):
        for data in train_loader:
            img, _ = data
            img_noisy = img + noise * torch.randn(*img.shape)
            img_noisy = torch.clip(img_noisy, 0, 1)
            recon = model(img_noisy)
            loss = criterion(recon, img)
            optimizer.zero_grad()
            loss.backward()
            optimizer.step()

        outputs.append((epoch, img_noisy, recon))
        print(f"Epoch [{epoch+1}/{num_epochs}], Loss: {loss.item():.4f}")




    # ==================== YOUR CODE ENDS HERE ===================
    return outputs

4. Variational Autoencoder¶
The Variational Autoencoder (VAE) is an advanced form of autoencoder with the unique ability to generate new samples that are similar to the original dataset. In the context of the attached image, let's break down how the VAE operates and the specific components that allow it to function as a generative model:


    

  1. Encoding Network (conv): The encoding network takes an input image, in this case, a picture of a cat, and passes it through convolutional layers (denoted as "conv"). This network compresses the image into a lower-dimensional space, capturing the most significant features. The encoding network's output is not just a single point but a distribution described by the next two components.
    

    2. 

  2. Mean and Standard Deviation Vectors: The encoder produces two vectors representing the parameters of a Gaussian distribution: a mean () vector and a standard deviation () vector. These vectors describe where the encoded representation of the input image lies in the latent space and how it's spread out. The Gaussian distribution is chosen because of its mathematical properties, which simplify the sampling process and help in regularizing the latent space.
    

    3. 

  3. Sampled Latent Vector: Instead of a deterministic output, we get a random sample from the Gaussian distribution defined by our mean and standard deviation vectors. This is what makes the VAE variationalit introduces variability by sampling from the distribution. This step is crucial for the generative aspect of the VAE, as it allows the model to produce new images that are variations of the input.
    

    4. 

  4. Decoding Network (deconv): The sampled latent vector is then passed to the decoding network, which typically consists of deconvolutional (or transposed convolutional) layers. The decoder takes the sampled latent vector and reconstructs it back into an image. For the VAE to work effectively, the decoder must be able to take any point from the latent space and map it back to a plausible image.
    

    5. 

  5. Output Image: The output is a reconstructed image that, ideally, closely resembles the input. However, because we're sampling from a distribution, the VAE can also generate new images that weren't in the training set by picking different points in the latent space.
    

    6. 



To ensure the encoder produces a latent space that follows a unit Gaussian distribution, a constraint is enforced using the Kullback-Leibler (KL) divergence in the loss function. The KL divergence measures how one probability distribution diverges from a second, expected probability distribution. In the case of VAEs, it helps to ensure that the latent vectors follow the desired distribution, enabling the model to sample effectively and generate new data points.


The figure below demonstrates the flow from input to the encoded representation, through sampling and back to the reconstructed output. The VAE's power lies in its ability to not just reconstruct inputs but also to explore the latent space and create new instances that are similar to the original data, making it a powerful tool for generative tasks.

# dimensions of latent space
zdim = 25

# Variational Autoencoder
class VAE(nn.Module):
    def __init__(self):
        super(VAE, self).__init__()

        # =================== START LOOKING FOR ERRORS HERE ==================
        # encoder
        self.fc1 = nn.Linear(28 * 28, 350) # Correcting the input dimension of MNIST to 28 x 28
        self.fc2m = nn.Linear(350, zdim)  # mu layer
        self.fc2s = nn.Linear(350, zdim)  # sd layer
        self.relu = nn.ReLU()

        # decoder
        self.fc3 = nn.Linear(zdim, 350)
        self.fc4 = nn.Linear(350, 28 * 28) #Correcting according to MNIST
        self.sigmoid = nn.Sigmoid()

    def encode(self, x):
        h1 = self.relu(self.fc1(x))
        return self.fc2m(h1), self.fc2s(h1) #Typically it's better to keep latent spaces linear(removing ReLU)

    # reparameterize
    def reparameterize(self, mu, logvar):
        if self.training:
            std = logvar.mul(0.5).exp_()
            eps = std.data.new(std.size()).normal_()
            return eps.mul(std).add_(mu)
        else:
            return mu

    def decode(self, z):
        h3 = self.relu(self.fc3(z))
        return self.sigmoid(self.fc4(h3)) #Only signmoid should be used. Removing ReLU

    def forward(self, x):
        mu, logvar = self.encode(x.view(-1, 28 * 28)) #Incorrect dimension. should be 28 x 28. 1 should be -1
        # =================== END LOOKING FOR ERRORS HERE ==================
        z = self.reparameterize(mu, logvar)
        return self.decode(z), mu, logvar



     























As mentioned previously, the loss function for VAE are unique and use Kullback-Leibler divergence measure to force distribution to match unit Gaussian.



















In [ ]:



     


def loss_function(recon_x, x, mu, logvar):
    bce = F.binary_cross_entropy(recon_x, x.view(-1, 28 * 28))
    kld = -0.5 * torch.sum(1 + logvar - mu.pow(2) - logvar.exp())
    kld /= batch_size * 28 * 28
    return bce + kld



     



















In [ ]:



     


def train(model, num_epochs = 1, batch_size = 64, learning_rate = 1e-3):
    model.train() #train mode
    torch.manual_seed(42)

    train_loader = torch.utils.data.DataLoader(datasets.MNIST('data',
               train=True, download=True, transform=transforms.ToTensor()),
               batch_size = batch_size, shuffle = True)

    optimizer = optim.Adam(model.parameters(), learning_rate)

    for epoch in range(num_epochs):
      for data in train_loader:
          img, _ = data

          recon, mu, logvar = model(img)
          loss = loss_function(recon, img, mu, logvar)
          loss.backward()
          optimizer.step()
          optimizer.zero_grad()

      print('Epoch:{}, Loss:{:.4f}'.format(epoch+1, float(loss)))
